description.plain:
Dominique Armani Jones (born December 3, 1994) better known by his stage name Lil Baby, has established himself as a global force from the Atlanta hip-hop scene. From growing up with fellow Atlanta rapper, Young Thug to many arrests and struggles with poverty, Baby has experienced tremendous grown since starting to rap in 2017.

Raised by his single mother, Baby was born into poverty with his two sisters and one brother. He lived off of food stamps and government assistance. In January 2012, he was arrested and charged with burglary. Later that year in August, he attempted to drop out of tenth grade but once again was arrested for possession of dangerous drugs. Two more marijuana possessions and one more theft charge put him in jail for two years. It was during his time in jail when Quality Control Music’s Pee and Coach K encouraged Baby to pursue a career in rapping.

He released his first mixtape on April 14, 2017, with Perfect Timing. The project features fellow Atlanta rappers, Lil Yachty, frequent collaborator Gunna, and childhood friend, Young Thug. Baby immediately rose to fame and attracted many listeners. This led him to drop two more mixtapes, Harder Than Hard and Too Hard, in the same year.

Baby’s debut studio album, Harder Than Ever peaked on the US Billboard 200 at the number 3 spot. The tape’s lead single, “Southside,” peaked at number 79 on the US Billboard Hot 100 while the second single, “Yes Indeed,” features Drake and topped off at number 6 on the charts.

Following the release of Drip Harder, a collaborative album with Gunna, Lil Baby released his fourth mixtape, Street Gossip. His February 2020 sophomore studio album, My Turn, went on to become the best selling album in the United States. The deluxe version of album features the viral hit “We Paid” with 42 Dugg.

songs.title: Close Friends

description.plain:
On this song, Lil Baby discusses the importance of becoming “Close Friends” with a woman before dating her. However, their relationship has soured due to Baby’s unfaithful actions, and he’s now pleading to her to love him again.

Jayda Cheaves, Lil Baby’s girlfriend and the mother of his child, first previewed a portion of this song on Instagram Live on May 31, 2018. The song is likely about their relationship, as Baby publicly admitted to cheating on Cheaves in April 2018.

Alongside “Deep End,” this is the second of two solo songs by Baby on Drip Harder.

songs.title: Freestyle

description.plain:
One of Atlanta, Georgia native Lil Baby’s breakout hits, “Freestyle” helped to introduce the rapper to audiences back in November 2017. The track’s lyrics address Baby’s rise to stardom as well as his usage of the recreational drug lean. In a May 2018 Breakfast Club interview, Lil Baby discussed his decision to eventually stop using lean:

That shit started fuckin' with me… like, breathe different, talk different, feel different, like, everything.

“Freestyle” was an early contributor towards Lil Baby’s successful career: the song’s music video, which was released on November 5, 2017, has accumulated over 300 million views. The track eventually appeared on Baby’s December 2017 mixtape Too Hard.

songs.title: On Me

description.plain:
Lil Baby reflects on how he deals with wealth and success on the long-awaited “On Me.” While the song finds Baby depicting his lavish lifestyle, the rapper also gets introspective, acknowledging his weaknesses and taking a wiser approach to his spending.

The song was first teased on October 7, 2020, by IJU Productions, the production company of the track’s accompanying music video. Multiple excerpts were further teased in late 2020 by Baby and his girlfriend, Jayda Cheaves.

description.plain:
“The Bigger Picture” is a protest song from Lil Baby, featuring the rapper commenting on police brutality and systemic racism in America in the wake of the murder of George Floyd.

The track comes just days after Baby went out and protested on the streets of Atlanta on June 8, 2020. At the protest, Baby was a leading force, leading the crowd on his bicycle (as depicted on the single’s cover art) as well as handing out protestors supplies and money and speaking in front of the crowd when they reached the march’s destination of Georgia’s State Capitol Building.

songs.title: Emotionally Scarred

description.plain:
“Emotionally Scarred” finds Lil Baby looking back at the influence that his old hood life left on his mindset. The rapper recalls being poor and explains that his come-up forced him to cut off many people from his entourage. A few days before the release of My Turn, Baby told The New York Times:

I don’t miss my old life at all. Period.

The three-minute song is one of the five tracks on My Turn produced by frequent collaborator Twysted Genius and  stands out as one of the breakout hits from the album.

description.plain:
“Woah” is the second single from Lil Baby’s sophomore studio album, My Turn. On the track, he taunts his haters and raps about the luxuries of his lifestyle. The song is seemingly named after the “Woah,” (or “Hit the Woah”), a popular dance that originated in Texas in the mid-2010s and went viral on the Internet, most notably on TikTok.

After announcing the track on October 26, 2019, Baby teased a video snippet of it on November 1, in which he appears doing the “Woah” dance.

The main difference between the final version and the leaked version is that the leaked version has two more lines at the end of the first verse, then the song ends, with no repetition of the chorus and no second verse.

description.plain:
“Commercial” marks Lil Baby’s and Lil Uzi Vert’s second collaboration. Baby originally announced that he would probably never release this song after he previewed his first verse in late 2019.

The song was however announced to be part of Baby’s sophomore album My Turn before being leaked in its entirety a few days before the release of the album. Uzi’s verse was most likely recorded in the month before the song’s release, given Lil Uzi’s allusion to Kobe Bryant’s passing away in January 2020.

description.plain:
On “Forever,” Lil Baby and Lil Wayne discuss their refusal to sell out to the evils of the rap game and forever remain true to themselves. This marks the second official collaboration between the two.

A snippet of the song was first posted in May 2019, and Baby would also preview Wayne’s verse months later. In January 2020, the song leaked in its entirety before receiving an official release on My Turn. The final version has a number of minor differences in the instrumental and vocal effects.

“Social Distancing“ is a standout track off of the deluxe of My Turn. On the track, Lil Baby uses the current social distancing recommendation – due to the COVID-19 pandemic – as a metaphor to emphasize how far ahead of the competition he is. Dropping references to expensive items and rich girls, Baby boasts about his lifestyle with fame.

On April 14, Baby teased the track by tweeting a line from the track:

This dynamic duo rap about expensive clothing, drugs, cars, chains and women, while repeatedly boasting about the value of the merchandise they own in their closet, and expressing how it could sustain their lifestyle if they were to ever be in financial straits. The pair also likens themselves to Hugh Hefner and mention singer Rihanna during this high-powered banger.

description.plain:
“Errbody” is a single released by Atlanta rapper Lil Baby. After his birthday, Baby blessed the fans with two surprise releases and this track is one of them. After a very successful 2020, he released this song with an official video alongside it.

https://twitter.com/lilbaby4PF/status/1334545466822959105

Throughout the song, Baby drops a number of names including athletes and other artists. He makes it clear in the hook that his fashion sense and appearance can’t be compared to anyone. He talks about his money and spendings in the single. He also said his biggest challenges outside of the music industry are to stay solid and not lose anything. Baby says:

Nowadays a lot of people depend on me. It’s a hard challenge for me, with all the distractions and shit. So that’s like the main thing to me, managing my money the right way.”

description.plain:
With “Get Ugly,” Lil Baby introduces the listener to the ambitious mood of My Turn, his sophomore album.

The song is produced by fellow Atlanta native ATL Jacob and finds Lil Baby rapping about how far he’s come, as well as elaborating on his current lifestyle. The triumphant tone carried by the lyrics of “Get Ugly” is in line with that featured in Baby’s previous intro songs, such as 2018’s “Global” and “Intro (Harder Than Ever).”
